00:15:50.770 --> 00:15:53.770
And if I bought 10 sweaters,

00:15:53.770 --> 00:15:56.690
and then you can predefined a phrase called,

00:15:56.690 --> 00:16:00.570
I bought X, Y, and then X is the number,

00:16:00.570 --> 00:16:02.690
and Y is the product.

00:16:02.690 --> 00:16:06.090
And then you can create automation behind it

00:16:06.090 --> 00:16:08.730
to exercise that particular sentence.

00:16:08.730 --> 00:16:12.290
So very easy to convert that sentence into,

00:16:12.290 --> 00:16:15.090
buy sweaters 10,

00:16:16.290 --> 00:16:18.570
that's like an action line.

00:16:18.570 --> 00:16:22.130
And then all you have to do is automate that action.

00:16:22.130 --> 00:16:23.770
And when you look at it,

00:16:24.690 --> 00:16:27.770
the organizing in that way makes it more manageable.

00:16:27.770 --> 00:16:29.690
Actions are much easier to manage

00:16:29.690 --> 00:16:33.970
and to automate and sentences.

00:16:33.970 --> 00:16:36.000
At least that's what I think.

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:39.480
Is, so many of our listeners are,

00:16:39.480 --> 00:16:40.840
as Alan pointed out,

00:16:40.840 --> 00:16:45.200
are fans of BDD and TDD.

00:16:45.200 --> 00:16:50.200
Is that what you would advise our audience

00:16:50.920 --> 00:16:53.800
around the difference between,

00:16:53.840 --> 00:16:57.920
say open source tools like Cucumber and others

00:16:57.920 --> 00:17:03.300
that enable BDD automation versus an ABT strategy?

00:17:03.540 --> 00:17:06.260
I would personally,

00:17:06.260 --> 00:17:10.860
I would want to work with the keywords.

00:17:10.860 --> 00:17:13.700
It's more efficient, simpler,

00:17:13.700 --> 00:17:15.380
the sentences,

00:17:15.380 --> 00:17:18.180
it has a tendency to kind of get out of control

00:17:18.180 --> 00:17:21.020
and multiple people.

00:17:21.020 --> 00:17:22.620
And let's say you have a project team

00:17:22.700 --> 00:17:25.380
with many, many people,

00:17:25.380 --> 00:17:28.500
different people that come up with different sentences.

00:17:28.500 --> 00:17:29.900
And to paraphrase you,

00:17:29.900 --> 00:17:32.980
if you have 10 people creating tests

00:17:32.980 --> 00:17:36.300
and coming up with a sentence for buying sweaters,

00:17:36.300 --> 00:17:40.060
there will be 11 sentences saying the same thing.

00:17:40.060 --> 00:17:42.820
It's very difficult to standardize language.

00:17:42.820 --> 00:17:44.020
While keywords,

00:17:44.020 --> 00:17:45.780
and they're almost like function calls,

00:17:45.780 --> 00:17:48.220
that's fairly easy to organize

00:17:48.220 --> 00:17:53.220
and to define and to agree on in a team.

00:17:53.700 --> 00:17:55.540
And then because of that tool,

00:17:55.540 --> 00:17:58.180
you can easily translate from one to the other.

00:17:58.180 --> 00:18:01.380
And doesn't even matter what keyword tool you use,

00:18:01.380 --> 00:18:06.300
and that's a fairly straightforward conversion.

00:18:06.300 --> 00:18:07.900
So I would personally,

00:18:07.900 --> 00:18:10.260
if I have to do a big testing project,

00:18:10.260 --> 00:18:12.380
I would try to write the test

00:18:12.380 --> 00:18:14.460
and organize the test as keywords

00:18:14.460 --> 00:18:16.780
when I have to present it to somebody

00:18:16.780 --> 00:18:19.140
who is not part of the team,

00:18:19.140 --> 00:18:22.490
then I might translate it into the sentences.

00:18:22.490 --> 00:18:25.810
One of the things that Alan,

00:18:25.810 --> 00:18:28.280
I don't know if you know,

00:18:28.280 --> 00:18:31.280
back in the day,

00:18:34.580 --> 00:18:39.140
so I did play my hand in ABT.

00:18:39.140 --> 00:18:42.340
And one of the things that I found that's really nice

00:18:42.340 --> 00:18:47.760
is it often directly ports into code.

00:18:48.820 --> 00:18:52.460
And so one of the benefits that I've discovered

00:18:52.460 --> 00:18:54.260
is when people go read my code,

00:18:54.260 --> 00:18:56.260
they're not reading Devs,

00:18:56.260 --> 00:19:00.340
they're not having to follow pointers, right?

00:19:00.340 --> 00:19:04.660
The methods and the objects used

00:19:04.660 --> 00:19:08.300
read so very similar to the same test cases

00:19:08.300 --> 00:19:13.140
that I may have designed in my test architecture doc.

00:19:13.140 --> 00:19:14.900
Yeah, that is true.

00:19:14.980 --> 00:19:18.500
In fact, you're doing testing and automation,

00:19:18.500 --> 00:19:21.140
it is very close to development.

00:19:21.140 --> 00:19:26.140
And you see that developers feel very at home

00:19:26.140 --> 00:19:28.020
with the actions

00:19:28.020 --> 00:19:30.740
because they see it as function calls.

00:19:30.740 --> 00:19:33.500
And even if you don't want to use a keyword tool

00:19:33.500 --> 00:19:35.460
and like our own tool,

00:19:35.460 --> 00:19:38.380
you could just put it in a source file

00:19:38.380 --> 00:19:40.460
and just make function calls out of it.

00:19:40.460 --> 00:19:43.980
I think you would achieve more or less the same result.

00:19:43.980 --> 00:19:46.220
And I do not believe that you have to go

00:19:46.220 --> 00:19:50.060
to natural language sentences to develop the test.

00:19:50.060 --> 00:19:56.500
And that's more like to create a negative to share.

00:19:56.500 --> 00:19:58.180
It's a bit like COBOL

00:19:58.180 --> 00:20:00.580
and the programming language with COBOL

00:20:00.580 --> 00:20:02.900
many years ago came to the market.

00:20:02.900 --> 00:20:04.980
That was even well before my time.

00:20:05.980 --> 00:20:10.380
The idea was that you would use natural language, English,

00:20:10.380 --> 00:20:13.140
to create your software.

00:20:13.140 --> 00:20:16.140
And that it would make it easier to create software.

00:20:16.140 --> 00:20:19.060
Well, history has started otherwise.

00:20:19.060 --> 00:20:23.980
And the more successful language now we see C++ and Java,

00:20:23.980 --> 00:20:28.840
which does not look like natural language at all.

00:20:28.840 --> 00:20:33.220
Well, so speaking up as a representative

00:20:33.220 --> 00:20:36.820
of the up and coming data science community,

00:20:36.820 --> 00:20:41.140
I'm gonna state that I think COBOL was probably a good idea

00:20:41.140 --> 00:20:45.680
but its time was too early.

00:20:45.680 --> 00:20:50.680
I do think the advances of natural language programming,

00:20:51.400 --> 00:20:53.960
I think we're gonna see programming

00:20:53.960 --> 00:20:56.160
through natural language within our lifetime

00:20:56.160 --> 00:20:59.840
in a way that actually works.

00:20:59.840 --> 00:21:01.800
Yeah, I would say you probably want to wait

00:21:01.800 --> 00:21:04.150
until it actually works.

00:21:04.150 --> 00:21:06.070
And you can't do more of that.

00:21:06.070 --> 00:21:08.690
Kind of like with self-driving cars, right?

00:21:08.690 --> 00:21:09.530
Yes.

00:21:10.210 --> 00:21:14.920
So love the idea of using action-based testing

00:21:14.920 --> 00:21:18.280
for functional testing, behavioral testing.

00:21:18.280 --> 00:21:22.120
Do you use it for other kinds of testing

00:21:22.120 --> 00:21:23.320
or are there kinds of testing

00:21:23.320 --> 00:21:27.760
where action-based testing isn't appropriate?

00:21:27.760 --> 00:21:31.240
Well, I think it works.

00:21:31.240 --> 00:21:32.920
But the way I always say it,

00:21:32.920 --> 00:21:36.640
it works for every test that you write down.

00:21:36.640 --> 00:21:40.160
So there is a very important category of test called

00:21:41.120 --> 00:21:42.800
exploratory testing.

00:21:42.800 --> 00:21:45.840
Most of the listeners will probably be familiar with that.

00:21:45.840 --> 00:21:49.440
And people like Cam Kamer, James Bach, Michael Bolton.

00:21:51.000 --> 00:21:53.480
That's a different animal.

00:21:53.480 --> 00:21:57.600
You really interact with the system under test

00:21:57.600 --> 00:22:01.000
basically from a human manual perspective,

00:22:01.000 --> 00:22:03.040
usually manual perspective.

00:22:03.040 --> 00:22:06.640
And you kind of try to learn about the system under test.

00:22:06.640 --> 00:22:11.640
So you search your way through the system under test

00:22:11.800 --> 00:22:14.120
and you learn and at the same time,

00:22:14.120 --> 00:22:15.800
you're going to spot problems.

00:22:15.800 --> 00:22:19.000
You're going to see, hey, the color of the logo is wrong.

00:22:19.000 --> 00:22:20.600
The logo is missing.

00:22:20.600 --> 00:22:22.640
There might be things that you spot

00:22:22.640 --> 00:22:25.560
that you did not expect to go wrong.

00:22:25.560 --> 00:22:28.120
So you did not make a test case for them,

00:22:28.120 --> 00:22:32.130
but still it can be very important items.

00:22:32.130 --> 00:22:34.930
So that kind of testing,

00:22:34.930 --> 00:22:37.450
that's generally not something you will do

00:22:37.450 --> 00:22:39.650
with an action-based model.

00:22:39.650 --> 00:22:42.010
That does not mean that action-based test

00:22:42.010 --> 00:22:45.290
could not be exploratory design.

00:22:45.290 --> 00:22:49.850
When you create and test for a business process,

00:22:49.850 --> 00:22:52.410
nothing stops you from maybe either talk

00:22:52.410 --> 00:22:55.210
to the business people, the end users,

00:22:55.210 --> 00:22:58.170
try to understand that business process.

00:22:58.170 --> 00:23:00.490
And in that process of understanding,

00:23:00.490 --> 00:23:02.730
you get ideas for tests.

00:23:02.730 --> 00:23:06.650
And rather than just follow the steps in the UI.

00:23:06.650 --> 00:23:10.240
So that there is some similarity there.

00:23:10.240 --> 00:23:12.120
And I agree completely, yeah.

00:23:12.120 --> 00:23:16.400
On the other hand, if you have tests like non-UI tests

00:23:16.400 --> 00:23:19.240
and like embedded software or services,

00:23:19.240 --> 00:23:22.360
maybe with micro-services, anything like that,

00:23:22.360 --> 00:23:26.000
that can be done very, very well with action-based testing.

00:23:26.000 --> 00:23:29.000
Action-based testing is even better in non-UI

00:23:29.000 --> 00:23:31.800
than it is in UI-based tests.

00:23:31.800 --> 00:23:33.640
So for that, it works well.

00:23:33.640 --> 00:23:38.020
I would probably even think

00:23:38.020 --> 00:23:39.900
that it could be used for unit testing,

00:23:39.900 --> 00:23:42.660
but I don't see that happening a lot.

00:23:42.660 --> 00:23:45.980
Most unit testing is just done by developers

00:23:45.980 --> 00:23:48.620
directly when they create the software.

00:23:48.620 --> 00:23:51.820
And then especially in agile,

00:23:51.820 --> 00:23:53.420
you tend to make the test first

00:23:53.420 --> 00:23:55.980
and then the function on the test.

00:23:55.980 --> 00:24:00.980
And I don't see that really doing with keywords or actions.

00:24:01.940 --> 00:24:06.940
So that middle area between the pure unit test on one hand

00:24:08.140 --> 00:24:11.220
and like the exploratory testing on the other hand,

00:24:11.220 --> 00:24:14.220
that entire area in between,

00:24:14.220 --> 00:24:17.920
the action-based testing works very well.

00:24:17.920 --> 00:24:20.800
What about things like load, stress, and perf testing?

00:24:20.800 --> 00:24:24.160
Could you find applications for action-based testing there?

00:24:24.160 --> 00:24:25.480
Yeah, absolutely.

00:24:25.480 --> 00:24:29.520
And one of the very first action-based projects I did,

00:24:29.520 --> 00:24:31.120
I was still in the Netherlands,

00:24:31.240 --> 00:24:33.000
and you guys didn't mention it,

00:24:33.000 --> 00:24:34.720
I am from the Netherlands.

00:24:34.720 --> 00:24:37.040
That was for the European Stock Exchange.

00:24:37.040 --> 00:24:41.040
And there we did a test with 40 laptops

00:24:43.840 --> 00:24:48.080
just to emulate the trading process.

00:24:48.080 --> 00:24:51.120
And so that goes very well with actions.

00:24:51.120 --> 00:24:54.240
You just make the scenarios with actions

00:24:54.240 --> 00:24:56.760
and then you use more actions

00:24:56.760 --> 00:24:58.320
to kind of populate the machines

00:24:58.320 --> 00:25:01.040
and get them started and get the results.

00:25:01.840 --> 00:25:04.080
So there might be actions like generate load

00:25:04.080 --> 00:25:09.080
and there might be an action like check response time

00:25:09.280 --> 00:25:11.720
and with a value of let's say 10,

00:25:11.720 --> 00:25:16.040
meaning if it is not there within 10 seconds, it fails.

00:25:16.040 --> 00:25:20.540
So that basically goes very well.

00:25:20.540 --> 00:25:21.540
All right, that's good to know.

00:25:21.540 --> 00:25:22.740
I wasn't thinking about that.

00:25:22.740 --> 00:25:23.740
That's good information.

00:25:26.460 --> 00:25:27.500
I think one last question,

00:25:27.500 --> 00:25:28.340
then we'll give you a chance

00:25:28.340 --> 00:25:30.780
to tell us what we should have asked you.

00:25:30.780 --> 00:25:32.940
I have a saying I've used for a long time

00:25:32.940 --> 00:25:34.940
around test design that says,

00:25:34.940 --> 00:25:37.100
and this actually goes back to a minute ago,

00:25:37.100 --> 00:25:38.460
you're talking about the difference,

00:25:38.460 --> 00:25:40.940
like that spectrum of exploratory testing

00:25:40.940 --> 00:25:42.860
versus what should be automated.

00:25:42.860 --> 00:25:45.500
And a line I've used for several years is

00:25:45.500 --> 00:25:48.340
that you should automate 100% of the tests

00:25:48.340 --> 00:25:50.760
that should be automated.

00:25:50.760 --> 00:25:53.040
So I'm curious what sort of,

00:25:53.040 --> 00:25:54.520
and that's the test design challenge

00:25:54.520 --> 00:25:56.240
or a big part of the test design challenge

00:25:56.240 --> 00:25:59.720
is that heuristic of what sorts of testing

00:25:59.720 --> 00:26:02.040
should I automate versus what should I not try

00:26:02.040 --> 00:26:05.280
cause I'm not gonna get a good return on my investment.

00:26:05.280 --> 00:26:07.240
So what sort of heuristics you use

00:26:07.240 --> 00:26:08.800
to figure out what should be automated

00:26:08.800 --> 00:26:10.720
or how do you figure out like

00:26:10.720 --> 00:26:12.920
what do you wanna automate versus maybe

00:26:12.920 --> 00:26:15.280
what you would encourage clients

00:26:15.280 --> 00:26:17.200
or yourself to not automate?

00:26:17.200 --> 00:26:20.400
Yeah, that's one of my favorite questions.

00:26:20.400 --> 00:26:22.600
I always hope that people will ask.

00:26:24.360 --> 00:26:26.600
Essentially the answer is very simple.

00:26:26.600 --> 00:26:28.680
I automate everything.

00:26:28.680 --> 00:26:33.520
That means I will automate every test that I write down.

00:26:33.520 --> 00:26:38.280
And so exploratory testing is a bit of an exception there.

00:26:38.280 --> 00:26:40.120
But if I write a test down,

00:26:40.120 --> 00:26:42.000
even on the back of an envelope,

00:26:42.000 --> 00:26:44.200
I will typically automate it

00:26:44.200 --> 00:26:46.440
unless it's really a one-time test.

00:26:46.440 --> 00:26:48.640
And like in this particular conversation,

00:26:48.640 --> 00:26:50.760
make sure the audio works.

00:26:50.760 --> 00:26:54.680
Once it works, we do the podcast and that's it.

00:26:54.680 --> 00:26:56.920
So we don't have to automate that test.

00:26:56.920 --> 00:27:00.640
With you guys, this is podcast number 57

00:27:00.640 --> 00:27:03.560
and you wanna make it up to at least 100.

00:27:04.560 --> 00:27:08.600
So maybe you want to kind of automate some of those tests

00:27:08.600 --> 00:27:10.440
because it's very minimal.

00:27:10.440 --> 00:27:13.920
Now I have a second point to make there

00:27:13.920 --> 00:27:15.720
and the question for me is not

00:27:15.720 --> 00:27:17.800
whether I should automate the test.

00:27:17.800 --> 00:27:21.160
The question for me is whether I should have that test,

00:27:21.160 --> 00:27:23.240
whether I should develop the test.

00:27:23.240 --> 00:27:26.560
So it is not the ROI on automation

00:27:26.560 --> 00:27:27.800
that counts for me,

00:27:27.800 --> 00:27:31.200
it's the ROI on testing that counts for me.

00:27:31.200 --> 00:27:33.480
And in the module approach,

00:27:33.480 --> 00:27:34.840
that's what I emphasize.

00:27:34.840 --> 00:27:36.880
Make a list of modules.

00:27:36.880 --> 00:27:38.560
And like in the ideal world,

00:27:38.560 --> 00:27:41.040
all the modules that you could possibly make,

00:27:41.040 --> 00:27:43.360
then be selective about the ones

00:27:43.360 --> 00:27:45.120
that you actually develop.

00:27:45.120 --> 00:27:46.080
Once you develop them,

00:27:46.080 --> 00:27:47.760
because you develop them with actions,

00:27:47.760 --> 00:27:49.360
with reusable keywords,

00:27:50.440 --> 00:27:52.640
it's almost hard not to automate them,

00:27:52.640 --> 00:27:54.640
to just automate them.

00:27:54.640 --> 00:27:56.280
Does that make sense?

00:27:57.200 --> 00:27:58.560
It does.

00:27:58.560 --> 00:28:01.440
Can you go a little bit deeper in terms of

00:28:01.440 --> 00:28:05.880
how you advise people to proactively evaluate

00:28:05.880 --> 00:28:09.230
the ROI of the test?

00:28:09.230 --> 00:28:10.630
Yes, absolutely.

00:28:11.670 --> 00:28:14.030
First of all, spend some time on it.

00:28:14.910 --> 00:28:17.550
That's the same with test design in general,

00:28:17.550 --> 00:28:19.550
just by thinking about it,

00:28:19.550 --> 00:28:20.990
how do I organize the test?

00:28:20.990 --> 00:28:22.790
What am I going to test?

00:28:22.790 --> 00:28:25.390
What is really a priority to test?

00:28:25.390 --> 00:28:28.190
You already get large, very good results.

00:28:28.190 --> 00:28:31.310
It helps enormously later on in the automation.

00:28:31.310 --> 00:28:34.110
Now, in the approach that I follow,

00:28:36.110 --> 00:28:38.030
it's almost like writing a book.

00:28:38.030 --> 00:28:39.390
When you write a book,

00:28:39.390 --> 00:28:41.390
the most difficult part of the book

00:28:41.390 --> 00:28:43.110
is the table of contents.

00:28:43.110 --> 00:28:45.590
That's what you have to really think about.

00:28:45.590 --> 00:28:48.750
And then once you have that table of contents,

00:28:48.750 --> 00:28:50.590
now writing the rest of the book is,

00:28:50.590 --> 00:28:51.950
of course, a lot more work.

00:28:51.950 --> 00:28:54.670
But assuming that you know what you're talking about,

00:28:54.670 --> 00:28:56.390
it's doable.

00:28:56.390 --> 00:28:58.510
It's just straightforward doing.

00:28:58.510 --> 00:29:00.190
It is that table of contents

00:29:00.190 --> 00:29:02.870
that you really have to sweat about it to think about.

00:29:02.870 --> 00:29:06.110
How am I going to organize my stuff?

00:29:06.110 --> 00:29:09.190
So the way I look at test design is very similar.

00:29:09.190 --> 00:29:11.870
You start with a high level test design phase

00:29:11.870 --> 00:29:15.190
in which you try to figure out

00:29:15.190 --> 00:29:18.670
what kind of tests am I going to make?

00:29:18.670 --> 00:29:20.270
What am I going to need?

00:29:20.270 --> 00:29:23.670
That results in a list of test modules

00:29:24.150 --> 00:29:28.040
in my terminology.

00:29:28.040 --> 00:29:29.360
And then you can make,

00:29:29.360 --> 00:29:30.920
put them in a spreadsheet, for example,

00:29:30.920 --> 00:29:33.880
make a column priority.

00:29:33.880 --> 00:29:35.320
Which one do I do first?

00:29:35.320 --> 00:29:37.240
Which one do I do last?

00:29:37.240 --> 00:29:39.120
Which one am I not going to do?

00:29:40.120 --> 00:29:41.800
Then you can,

00:29:41.800 --> 00:29:42.640
once you do that,

00:29:42.640 --> 00:29:45.830
then you can start developing those test modules.

00:29:45.830 --> 00:29:48.350
And there are always a couple that are very urgent.

00:29:48.350 --> 00:29:50.150
And there are always many that you

00:29:50.150 --> 00:29:53.120
don't care about that much.

00:29:53.120 --> 00:29:54.880
Oh, and another point there,

00:29:54.880 --> 00:29:57.560
is that's also the moment that you can go to

00:29:57.560 --> 00:30:02.560
managers or product owners or domain experts,

00:30:02.800 --> 00:30:05.480
developers, that you can start cooperating.

00:30:06.480 --> 00:30:10.400
