00:31:55.930 --> 00:31:59.050
I see testing as a profession.

00:31:59.050 --> 00:32:01.770
I believe there is such a thing as a good tester,

00:32:01.770 --> 00:32:04.250
somebody who can find problems,

00:32:04.250 --> 00:32:09.170
who can try unexpected situations and find bugs that way.

00:32:09.170 --> 00:32:13.770
Because most of the bugs are not so much coding bugs

00:32:13.770 --> 00:32:15.210
in my terminology,

00:32:15.370 --> 00:32:17.810
it's not so much like I specified it

00:32:17.810 --> 00:32:19.930
and the developer didn't build it,

00:32:19.930 --> 00:32:21.970
but the developer specified it himself,

00:32:21.970 --> 00:32:25.050
but he forgot the minus sign or something.

00:32:25.050 --> 00:32:28.850
Those had bugs happen that are usually quite easy to find

00:32:28.850 --> 00:32:31.050
and it's not such a common problem.

00:32:31.050 --> 00:32:35.050
The most of the bugs, the things that we call bugs,

00:32:35.050 --> 00:32:38.730
is you're not meeting an unexpected situation.

00:32:38.730 --> 00:32:41.770
Something happened, some input values happened

00:32:41.770 --> 00:32:43.490
that you didn't expect

00:32:43.490 --> 00:32:46.530
or you wrote something to the database that was wrong

00:32:46.530 --> 00:32:49.810
and another module gets into trouble because of it.

00:32:49.810 --> 00:32:51.810
So unexpected situation.

00:32:51.810 --> 00:32:56.450
To deal with that, testing can be very helpful.

00:32:56.450 --> 00:32:58.210
And I believe that is a profession.

00:32:58.210 --> 00:33:00.490
I don't believe a good developer

00:33:00.490 --> 00:33:02.970
is automatically a good tester.

00:33:02.970 --> 00:33:06.450
It is like, and I try to explain it,

00:33:06.450 --> 00:33:09.730
